1
00:00:04,895 --> 00:00:07,297
Hello, and welcome to Everyone Can Do PR.

2
00:00:08,177 --> 00:00:11,240
Today I'm going to tell you five things you should get right

3
00:00:11,580 --> 00:00:14,342
to talk to Brett Spetta and get more headlines,

4
00:00:14,402 --> 00:00:15,523
and five things you should avoid.

5
00:00:16,223 --> 00:00:17,724
Before I can tell you how you should do PR,

6
00:00:17,744 --> 00:00:18,885
I have to tell you two other things.

7
00:00:19,186 --> 00:00:21,167
One is please turn your cell phone off,

8
00:00:21,567 --> 00:00:22,888
and the other thing is please don't forget

9
00:00:22,908 --> 00:00:24,409
to evaluate the session by the end.

10
00:00:25,510 --> 00:00:27,912
So I think it's safe to assume that most of the people

11
00:00:27,952 --> 00:00:30,514
here in the room either have launched a game already

12
00:00:30,714 --> 00:00:31,915
or are about to launch a game.

13
00:00:32,585 --> 00:00:35,047
And whenever I have launched a game, it felt a bit like that.

14
00:00:35,808 --> 00:00:37,770
Your game is just like one of those little stars

15
00:00:37,810 --> 00:00:39,071
in the big gaming cosmos.

16
00:00:39,571 --> 00:00:41,793
And it's just so hard to get attention from anybody,

17
00:00:42,433 --> 00:00:45,636
be it press, be it streamers, be it YouTubers, be it players.

18
00:00:47,037 --> 00:00:48,298
And that's not only a feeling I have.

19
00:00:48,558 --> 00:00:49,319
That's actually the truth.

20
00:00:49,799 --> 00:00:52,802
If you just look at some numbers, in 2015 alone,

21
00:00:53,202 --> 00:00:55,063
there were over 3,000 games released on Steam.

22
00:00:55,732 --> 00:00:56,892
That makes eight games a day.

23
00:00:57,432 --> 00:01:00,514
And if we go a bit more crazy and we look into mobile,

24
00:01:00,554 --> 00:01:01,894
and it doesn't even count Google Play.

25
00:01:01,934 --> 00:01:02,915
We're just talking iOS.

26
00:01:03,695 --> 00:01:06,436
Last year, there were over 160,000 games submitted.

27
00:01:07,077 --> 00:01:09,338
That makes 450 games a day.

28
00:01:09,918 --> 00:01:11,619
So that is your competition if you release a game.

29
00:01:12,179 --> 00:01:14,220
Of course, some of those games are weird rip-offs.

30
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:16,561
Some of them are not a competitor of you.

31
00:01:17,241 --> 00:01:20,342
But the point is, there's a lot of other games out there,

32
00:01:20,442 --> 00:01:22,043
and they also want attention from people.

33
00:01:23,344 --> 00:01:23,964
The good thing is.

34
00:01:24,809 --> 00:01:28,232
I think there are two solutions how you can still succeed.

35
00:01:28,292 --> 00:01:30,434
And they're both quite easy, at least technically.

36
00:01:31,135 --> 00:01:35,299
Number one is how to make it.

37
00:01:35,839 --> 00:01:37,861
But number one, you're one of those people.

38
00:01:39,903 --> 00:01:40,304
Easy, right?

39
00:01:40,584 --> 00:01:42,686
You're just so ridiculously good in what you do.

40
00:01:43,226 --> 00:01:44,868
You're just a Mozart of your generation.

41
00:01:44,888 --> 00:01:45,849
You just move people.

42
00:01:46,189 --> 00:01:49,192
Whatever you did is just so good that you don't really need PR.

43
00:01:50,353 --> 00:01:51,013
If you're that good.

44
00:01:51,821 --> 00:01:54,142
You cannot talk about your game at all, and somebody will

45
00:01:54,162 --> 00:01:55,283
discover it, and it will go big.

46
00:01:55,703 --> 00:01:58,704
Or you can talk way too much about your game, but still be

47
00:01:58,744 --> 00:01:59,244
successful.

48
00:02:01,045 --> 00:02:04,987
But the second path, and that is what 90% of other

49
00:02:05,027 --> 00:02:07,508
developers will encounter, 99%, I would say.

50
00:02:08,269 --> 00:02:10,750
The solution to still be successful is you make a

51
00:02:10,790 --> 00:02:14,171
really good game, and then you also make good PR, and then

52
00:02:14,865 --> 00:02:18,548
get the word out there. Because just making a good game is just not enough anymore.

53
00:02:18,808 --> 00:02:22,291
Those days are gone. I remember when I was little and I went into GameStop,

54
00:02:22,852 --> 00:02:26,475
there were every week there were two or three new games. That is the past.

55
00:02:27,696 --> 00:02:30,639
So today, we're going to look at five things you should get right,

56
00:02:31,259 --> 00:02:34,882
five things you shouldn't get right, five things you shouldn't do, and five future

57
00:02:34,902 --> 00:02:38,806
trends. And because one part of PR is also to set expectations

58
00:02:38,886 --> 00:02:39,046
right.

59
00:02:40,829 --> 00:02:43,590
We're going to talk a lot about the five things you need to get right.

60
00:02:43,690 --> 00:02:46,031
So there will be like 80 to 90 percent of the presentation,

61
00:02:46,051 --> 00:02:47,711
and then very shortly the other two topics.

62
00:02:49,772 --> 00:02:51,572
Some words about me before we start.

63
00:02:52,012 --> 00:02:53,233
My name is Thomas Reisenhecker.

64
00:02:53,693 --> 00:02:55,993
I'm from Austria. Currently I live in the UK in Brighton,

65
00:02:56,614 --> 00:02:59,734
and I work for Ico Partners, and we are a consulting and PR agency.

66
00:03:00,995 --> 00:03:04,516
I work on the PR side, and we cover a wide variety of games.

67
00:03:05,156 --> 00:03:06,817
There might be some really big games,

68
00:03:06,857 --> 00:03:09,017
we worked for a long time with League of Legends and with SMITE.

69
00:03:09,652 --> 00:03:13,954
but also a lot of smaller games like Too Dark, A Mellow Dungeon of the Endless, or fragments of him.

70
00:03:14,935 --> 00:03:20,338
Before I went into PR, I was a freelance video game journalist, so I also know the other side of the game.

71
00:03:21,138 --> 00:03:26,041
And my way from being press to being a PR person was actually just helping my friends out

72
00:03:26,642 --> 00:03:28,703
for the indie game, which turned out quite successful.

73
00:03:28,803 --> 00:03:34,906
So I also know how it is to work with very little knowledge in that sense, and also very little resources.

74
00:03:36,966 --> 00:03:39,908
What I won't cover in this talk is the basics of PR.

75
00:03:40,388 --> 00:03:42,209
They are also really important, but today we're

76
00:03:42,229 --> 00:03:44,131
going to talk about the five things you should focus on.

77
00:03:44,591 --> 00:03:45,832
There are also a lot of other basics,

78
00:03:45,892 --> 00:03:48,434
like how your website should look like, what is a press kit,

79
00:03:49,114 --> 00:03:50,655
what is a basic social media setup,

80
00:03:51,215 --> 00:03:52,596
how to write a press release properly,

81
00:03:52,837 --> 00:03:53,837
how to build a mailing list.

82
00:03:54,117 --> 00:03:55,478
If you're interested in those topics,

83
00:03:56,459 --> 00:03:58,260
you can find a presentation on that on my Twitter

84
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:01,342
and also on the GDC World Forum last year's GDC Europe.

85
00:04:04,546 --> 00:04:05,487
So let's get right into it.

86
00:04:05,567 --> 00:04:06,928
What are the five things you need to get right?

87
00:04:08,409 --> 00:04:09,790
Number one is positioning.

88
00:04:10,370 --> 00:04:11,591
And that sounds really easy.

89
00:04:11,711 --> 00:04:13,793
And I bet most people think they have figured it out.

90
00:04:14,693 --> 00:04:16,114
But I think also most people are wrong.

91
00:04:16,314 --> 00:04:19,437
Positioning your game right is extremely, really hard.

92
00:04:19,677 --> 00:04:21,458
But if you do it, that really pays off.

93
00:04:22,139 --> 00:04:25,161
Because otherwise, you will have a lot of PR efforts that

94
00:04:25,201 --> 00:04:27,723
just go nowhere, really, because you don't have a goal.

95
00:04:27,743 --> 00:04:28,903
You don't know what to focus on.

96
00:04:29,664 --> 00:04:31,986
So what you want to do is figure out one key message

97
00:04:32,386 --> 00:04:33,266
and one key artwork.

98
00:04:33,807 --> 00:04:34,788
That represents a game.

99
00:04:34,968 --> 00:04:36,468
That is the basic idea behind the game.

100
00:04:36,508 --> 00:04:37,809
Whenever you say the name of the game,

101
00:04:38,189 --> 00:04:39,309
the people should see in their head.

102
00:04:40,270 --> 00:04:42,691
So what I like to do is a test to figure out

103
00:04:42,851 --> 00:04:44,731
if I've got the positioning for a game right.

104
00:04:44,811 --> 00:04:47,613
Is just think about you're going to a dinner with your mom

105
00:04:47,673 --> 00:04:48,353
or with your friends.

106
00:04:48,873 --> 00:04:50,674
And you're really not interested in the video games.

107
00:04:51,314 --> 00:04:54,075
And then they're asking you, so what game are you working on?

108
00:04:54,715 --> 00:04:56,976
And then you have a really short attention window

109
00:04:57,076 --> 00:04:59,717
of about three to 10 seconds to explain what that game is about.

110
00:05:00,557 --> 00:05:03,420
And if you say, oh, it's root-like, a random generator

111
00:05:03,440 --> 00:05:06,323
with cool chip tune, and mom would start playing on the phone

112
00:05:06,343 --> 00:05:06,884
and that's it.

113
00:05:07,544 --> 00:05:08,385
You've lost her attention.

114
00:05:09,266 --> 00:05:12,289
But if you say, Goat Simulator, you'll be like, Goat Simulator?

115
00:05:12,570 --> 00:05:13,030
What's that?

116
00:05:13,631 --> 00:05:16,393
Or if you say, you're making a space game with ships

117
00:05:16,414 --> 00:05:18,596
that are as big as the Titanic, they'll probably be like, OK,

118
00:05:18,616 --> 00:05:19,437
that sounds interesting.

119
00:05:19,477 --> 00:05:20,398
They can picture something.

120
00:05:20,438 --> 00:05:21,018
They can connect.

121
00:05:21,859 --> 00:05:22,880
And that is the basic thing.

122
00:05:23,595 --> 00:05:26,618
You're not selling a game, you're always selling a story.

123
00:05:26,858 --> 00:05:28,980
Be it to players, but also mostly to press.

124
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:31,762
Because similar to your friends that don't like video games,

125
00:05:31,822 --> 00:05:33,324
they have a very short attention span,

126
00:05:33,684 --> 00:05:35,526
because press just gets flooded with new games.

127
00:05:37,608 --> 00:05:39,530
And also, a bit controversial statement,

128
00:05:39,670 --> 00:05:41,351
but if you figure out your positioning,

129
00:05:41,491 --> 00:05:44,534
I think it's totally fine to go back to the drawing board.

130
00:05:45,475 --> 00:05:46,916
We had that happening quite sometimes.

131
00:05:47,551 --> 00:05:50,392
that you think you figured out what a good positioning for a game is,

132
00:05:50,752 --> 00:05:55,113
then you have a press release, and then actually you see what players respond to,

133
00:05:55,593 --> 00:05:58,714
or what fans figure out and pick out what is actually interesting about the game.

134
00:05:59,294 --> 00:06:02,294
You shouldn't change your positioning every 10 minutes or a week before launch,

135
00:06:02,895 --> 00:06:05,375
but it doesn't hurt in the beginning to go back once or twice.

136
00:06:06,756 --> 00:06:10,716
And now I've just three examples from games that are hard to position,

137
00:06:10,936 --> 00:06:12,077
but they did it perfectly right.

138
00:06:12,677 --> 00:06:13,717
One is this War of Mine.

139
00:06:14,605 --> 00:06:16,745
And that game is an absolute PR nightmare.

140
00:06:16,945 --> 00:06:18,605
Because from far it looks like that.

141
00:06:19,126 --> 00:06:20,266
You cannot picture anything.

142
00:06:20,626 --> 00:06:21,626
It looks a bit boring.

143
00:06:22,206 --> 00:06:23,706
It doesn't have a real main character.

144
00:06:23,726 --> 00:06:29,167
The word war in the title already paints something

145
00:06:29,207 --> 00:06:31,148
like Call of Duty and a lot of ego shooting.

146
00:06:31,208 --> 00:06:32,848
It's already a bit weird.

147
00:06:34,208 --> 00:06:36,189
And what they did to prevent all those things

148
00:06:36,249 --> 00:06:37,989
from happening you had when you just read the title

149
00:06:38,009 --> 00:06:40,149
or see the screenshot from you getting bored,

150
00:06:40,289 --> 00:06:41,730
they're always using a sub-headline.

151
00:06:42,445 --> 00:06:45,426
And that sub-headline is, in war, not everyone is a soldier.

152
00:06:46,306 --> 00:06:49,287
And as soon as you see that, that immediately paints a

153
00:06:49,327 --> 00:06:49,967
picture in your head.

154
00:06:50,447 --> 00:06:52,367
You know that that game is probably not pro-war.

155
00:06:52,507 --> 00:06:53,787
It's probably not really patriotic.

156
00:06:54,768 --> 00:06:57,348
It doesn't have one strong protagonist, but a lot of

157
00:06:57,408 --> 00:06:59,448
people, and those people are not soldiers.

158
00:07:00,169 --> 00:07:02,389
So with that little line, which was probably really hard

159
00:07:02,429 --> 00:07:04,869
to come up with, they were doing a lot of

160
00:07:04,929 --> 00:07:05,750
positioning already.

161
00:07:07,090 --> 00:07:09,230
A similar example, or a different example, is a game

162
00:07:09,270 --> 00:07:10,110
called Axiom Verge.

163
00:07:11,105 --> 00:07:16,951
And Axiom Verge's app, look at that title, like, that doesn't mean anything. Axiom Verge is a weird thing.

164
00:07:18,973 --> 00:07:22,596
And also the key art, cannot picture a lot what the game is about.

165
00:07:23,337 --> 00:07:27,160
But if you know the game, you know it's quite a bit like a modern version of Super Metroid.

166
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:30,642
And that's the whole thing it communicates really.

167
00:07:30,743 --> 00:07:32,024
It has a really sci-fi title.

168
00:07:32,545 --> 00:07:36,430
The thing that the visual style is also quite Super Metroid-y.

169
00:07:36,871 --> 00:07:38,192
So they knew their target audience.

170
00:07:38,332 --> 00:07:40,055
They wanted to have Super Metroid fans.

171
00:07:40,115 --> 00:07:41,777
And that's exactly what they communicate.

172
00:07:41,797 --> 00:07:42,478
So that's OnSpot.

173
00:07:43,539 --> 00:07:46,543
And another game that was talked here about a lot is SuperHot.

174
00:07:48,420 --> 00:07:51,421
And SuperHead, technically, is a bit complicated to explain,

175
00:07:51,621 --> 00:07:53,822
but they just summed up their whole positioning

176
00:07:53,862 --> 00:07:56,882
in a straightforward sentence, an FPS game where time moves

177
00:07:56,942 --> 00:07:58,743
only when you move, and immediately you

178
00:07:58,783 --> 00:07:59,763
get what the game is about.

179
00:08:00,043 --> 00:08:00,943
So that's very well done.

180
00:08:03,364 --> 00:08:06,004
The second thing you need to get right is mastering new speeds.

181
00:08:07,024 --> 00:08:09,705
What I mean by that, every game has a certain amount

182
00:08:09,745 --> 00:08:12,226
of PR ammunition, and you have to really master

183
00:08:12,246 --> 00:08:15,826
that, how you position them and how you sum them up or not.

184
00:08:16,709 --> 00:08:18,650
Just imagine, every game has certain PR beats.

185
00:08:19,031 --> 00:08:20,251
They're definitely going to happen.

186
00:08:20,591 --> 00:08:22,613
You have the game announcement, you have the first screenshots,

187
00:08:22,653 --> 00:08:25,715
you have the first trailer, a beta start, a release date,

188
00:08:25,775 --> 00:08:26,135
a release.

189
00:08:26,195 --> 00:08:27,716
That's a thing you can talk about with press.

190
00:08:28,236 --> 00:08:30,798
But depending on how important you are, or how high your profile

191
00:08:30,838 --> 00:08:32,839
is, or how cool your game looks, you

192
00:08:32,879 --> 00:08:34,460
have to use those things very differently.

193
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:37,321
If you're Half-Life 3 and you're going to announce your game,

194
00:08:37,662 --> 00:08:38,782
people are going to go insane.

195
00:08:38,802 --> 00:08:39,783
There are a lot of articles.

196
00:08:39,843 --> 00:08:40,343
It's everywhere.

197
00:08:40,884 --> 00:08:42,404
First screenshots, people go crazy.

198
00:08:42,465 --> 00:08:43,685
First trailer, people go crazy.

199
00:08:44,289 --> 00:08:54,933
If you're a small indie dev making a jump and run that looks alrightish but not the best game ever, you announce it, no one will care. First screenshots, no one will care. First trailer, probably two people will care.

200
00:08:55,614 --> 00:09:05,198
But if you sum all those three things up, you have a pretty good announcement. You have a game announcement, brief screenshots and a trailer and quite some info, you have a much higher chance of getting covered.

201
00:09:05,838 --> 00:09:10,000
But that of course also means you've already wasted the first three points on that list.

202
00:09:11,188 --> 00:09:17,690
And that is really the art about knowing how much you have to use without wasting it to come through to press.

203
00:09:18,351 --> 00:09:22,452
And how you can master that is either by hiring an expert or becoming an expert.

204
00:09:22,612 --> 00:09:27,214
And by becoming an expert, I think the key is just you read loads of websites each day

205
00:09:27,794 --> 00:09:31,415
and just figure out what they write about and what is big enough for them to cover and what is not.

206
00:09:33,936 --> 00:09:37,498
But not also talking about which messages you give to press.

207
00:09:38,174 --> 00:09:40,496
It's also important in which timing that happens.

208
00:09:40,536 --> 00:09:41,736
And they can make quite a difference,

209
00:09:41,776 --> 00:09:42,637
but it's not hard to do.

210
00:09:43,397 --> 00:09:46,059
And at ICO, we looked at data from thousands of gaming

211
00:09:46,099 --> 00:09:48,921
websites around the world and when they publish articles.

212
00:09:50,462 --> 00:09:53,223
And as you can see, they have really high output in June

213
00:09:53,243 --> 00:09:53,964
because of E3.

214
00:09:54,004 --> 00:09:55,825
So that's probably a time you want to avoid if you're a

215
00:09:55,845 --> 00:09:56,425
small indie dev.

216
00:09:56,885 --> 00:09:58,807
Or you look at the Christmas period, where there's loads of

217
00:09:58,847 --> 00:09:59,607
articles coming up.

218
00:10:00,268 --> 00:10:02,689
It would be more clever for you to go for a summer for a

219
00:10:02,729 --> 00:10:03,690
big announcement or a launch.

220
00:10:04,855 --> 00:10:05,895
The same goes for weekdays.

221
00:10:06,095 --> 00:10:08,196
Unsurprisingly, press is not too happy

222
00:10:08,216 --> 00:10:10,837
about working on weekends, which is why there are less articles

223
00:10:10,857 --> 00:10:11,317
on weekends.

224
00:10:11,797 --> 00:10:13,178
Also, Mondays start a bit slow.

225
00:10:13,318 --> 00:10:15,359
Fridays start a bit early because the weekend starts.

226
00:10:15,699 --> 00:10:17,300
So if you have the option, you want

227
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:20,081
to choose a day between Tuesday and Thursday.

228
00:10:20,341 --> 00:10:22,242
Of course, that doesn't guarantee you get covered,

229
00:10:22,442 --> 00:10:23,542
but it gives you better chances.

230
00:10:25,043 --> 00:10:26,763
And also, on the day itself, it depends

231
00:10:27,284 --> 00:10:28,204
what time you want to pick.

232
00:10:29,364 --> 00:10:31,645
Always go for office hours, even for bigger games.

233
00:10:31,705 --> 00:10:33,386
I can tell you, it makes a huge difference

234
00:10:33,426 --> 00:10:34,527
if you're outside of office hours.

235
00:10:35,887 --> 00:10:37,348
And keep the time zones in mind.

236
00:10:37,468 --> 00:10:40,310
What we usually do if you want to cover US and European press,

237
00:10:40,350 --> 00:10:44,552
we go for that timing, which is 6 PST is 2 GMT.

238
00:10:44,652 --> 00:10:46,153
So you get the US people in the morning

239
00:10:46,294 --> 00:10:48,195
and the European people early in the afternoon

240
00:10:48,275 --> 00:10:49,476
if you send out communications.

241
00:10:51,117 --> 00:10:52,858
And also keep local bank holidays in mind.

242
00:10:53,258 --> 00:10:54,159
May sound a bit silly.

243
00:10:54,279 --> 00:10:55,880
Already happened quite a lot of times

244
00:10:56,280 --> 00:10:58,722
that you just forget that it's a big bank holiday in the UK

245
00:10:58,802 --> 00:10:59,362
or in the US.

246
00:10:59,462 --> 00:11:00,623
And then you miss out a lot of press

