00:21:01,668 --> 00:21:03,549
launch trailer, previous reviews, interviews,

500
00:21:03,629 --> 00:21:04,609
it did quite some PR.

501
00:21:05,209 --> 00:21:07,150
And on the right, just the pirate PR stunt.

502
00:21:07,812 --> 00:21:11,415
And just the Pirate PR stunt alone, that one PR beat of

503
00:21:11,515 --> 00:21:14,618
making a little, a leaky second version and sending out a

504
00:21:14,658 --> 00:21:17,620
press release about that, got more than half of the coverage

505
00:21:17,641 --> 00:21:18,962
than all the other coverage combined.

506
00:21:19,402 --> 00:21:20,163
So really good for them.

507
00:21:21,604 --> 00:21:26,088
In terms of sales, we see on the left in the blue the iOS

508
00:21:26,388 --> 00:21:29,290
sales, with the iOS launch going up, going down, quite

509
00:21:29,350 --> 00:21:32,713
normal, the Android launch boosts iOS a bit, Android

510
00:21:32,733 --> 00:21:35,495
starts to sell, and then we have the Android PR stunt,

511
00:21:35,616 --> 00:21:35,876
and then.

512
00:21:36,530 --> 00:21:38,791
The Android PR sales really went up.

513
00:21:39,452 --> 00:21:42,213
And I think it's also one of the few games that had nearly

514
00:21:42,233 --> 00:21:45,114
the same amount of iOS and Android sales because of that

515
00:21:45,234 --> 00:21:49,916
PR stunt.

516
00:21:50,076 --> 00:21:52,597
Number five for things you should get right are events.

517
00:21:53,337 --> 00:21:55,118
And there's a lot to talk about events.

518
00:21:56,538 --> 00:21:58,839
They're great, absolutely fantastic for networking.

519
00:21:59,360 --> 00:22:00,480
They're great for recruiting.

520
00:22:00,600 --> 00:22:01,861
They're good for getting inspiration.

521
00:22:01,921 --> 00:22:02,801
They're good for feedback.

522
00:22:03,725 --> 00:22:04,946
Sometimes they're good for press.

523
00:22:05,166 --> 00:22:06,626
But if you look solely at PR, there's

524
00:22:06,646 --> 00:22:09,707
a very limited number of events that pay off for you.

525
00:22:10,547 --> 00:22:15,249
We, again, have a graph which events get covered by media.

526
00:22:15,789 --> 00:22:16,409
How many times?

527
00:22:19,050 --> 00:22:21,451
What we don't see in the graph is E3.

528
00:22:21,671 --> 00:22:25,072
Because if E3 would be on there, you would still see games coming.

529
00:22:25,092 --> 00:22:26,732
The other thing would just shrink down

530
00:22:26,752 --> 00:22:27,693
and you couldn't see them anymore.

531
00:22:28,313 --> 00:22:31,514
But also for an indie, E3 is quite hard to reach.

532
00:22:31,694 --> 00:22:32,794
So we left it out for that graph.

533
00:22:33,615 --> 00:22:36,156
And as you can see, Gamescom gets a lot of articles.

534
00:22:36,616 --> 00:22:38,236
Tokyo Game Show gets a lot of articles.

535
00:22:38,616 --> 00:22:39,437
GDC as well.

536
00:22:39,617 --> 00:22:41,937
But everything after that, it really gets more quiet.

537
00:22:42,877 --> 00:22:44,658
So I'm not saying going to events is bad.

538
00:22:44,758 --> 00:22:47,618
I'm just saying, as an indie, probably don't go to every

539
00:22:47,658 --> 00:22:49,159
event if you don't have to show anything.

540
00:22:49,639 --> 00:22:51,639
I know it's quite cool at the moment because of Rami, and it

541
00:22:51,699 --> 00:22:52,419
really works for him.

542
00:22:52,840 --> 00:22:54,080
I'm not sure if it works for everyone.

543
00:22:57,260 --> 00:22:58,201
Five common pitfalls.

544
00:23:00,481 --> 00:23:01,801
What you shouldn't do in indie games PR.

545
00:23:03,082 --> 00:23:05,643
First of all, biggest of all, it's just doing too little too late.

546
00:23:05,883 --> 00:23:09,384
I know it's really hard to make a game, I know it takes a lot of time and effort,

547
00:23:10,225 --> 00:23:13,886
but also, if you spend one or two or three years making a game

548
00:23:13,986 --> 00:23:17,447
and then don't take the extra few months to get a PR campaign off the ground,

549
00:23:17,727 --> 00:23:19,268
that's a shame and it happens quite a lot.

550
00:23:21,513 --> 00:23:23,374
Playing J and D cards doesn't work anymore.

551
00:23:23,714 --> 00:23:25,516
It was cool a few years back, saying,

552
00:23:25,576 --> 00:23:26,617
we're just one developer.

553
00:23:26,637 --> 00:23:27,657
We're working in a basement.

554
00:23:28,038 --> 00:23:28,898
That doesn't work anymore.

555
00:23:28,938 --> 00:23:29,559
Nobody cares.

556
00:23:30,299 --> 00:23:32,141
If you tell that to press, it's just not impressive.

557
00:23:32,561 --> 00:23:34,562
There are a few examples where somebody is alone

558
00:23:34,602 --> 00:23:35,963
and pulls up something insane.

559
00:23:36,524 --> 00:23:38,745
But in general, I think that's not a good angle for press

560
00:23:38,825 --> 00:23:39,326
to talk to them.

561
00:23:41,564 --> 00:23:44,705
Number 3 is again, I can't stress it enough, a poor technical trailer.

562
00:23:45,066 --> 00:23:47,527
That's the one time people are going to look at your game for sure.

563
00:23:47,947 --> 00:23:51,870
And if you just put it together somehow and you show how many shaders and features you have,

564
00:23:51,890 --> 00:23:53,711
that's not something people care about.

565
00:23:53,991 --> 00:23:55,792
You have to transport your one key message.

566
00:23:57,773 --> 00:23:59,694
I think also a lot of indies don't repackage enough.

567
00:24:00,215 --> 00:24:03,997
What I mean by that is, if you announce your game and it doesn't get press coverage,

568
00:24:04,557 --> 00:24:05,298
just announce it again.

569
00:24:05,318 --> 00:24:08,500
It's a bit sleazy, but it does work quite sometime.

570
00:24:09,716 --> 00:24:12,579
And if it's not announced and if it's not out there, it just doesn't officially exist.

571
00:24:12,939 --> 00:24:14,221
So just don't care and try it again.

572
00:24:14,581 --> 00:24:17,244
Don't be too annoying, don't announce it like 50 times,

573
00:24:17,604 --> 00:24:19,466
but it doesn't hurt to give it a second or third try.

574
00:24:20,467 --> 00:24:23,090
A thing where we did that is a game called Too Dark, where we had

575
00:24:23,110 --> 00:24:28,696
a reveal teaser, which was nice and it worked nice. It got a few thousand views, it got media pick-up, all that.

576
00:24:29,257 --> 00:24:31,760
But we thought from the material that we have, it could be better.

577
00:24:32,492 --> 00:24:35,294
So after quite some time, we went back to the drawing board,

578
00:24:35,414 --> 00:24:37,715
took the trailer again, recycled it,

579
00:24:38,015 --> 00:24:39,736
let it cut by a professional company,

580
00:24:40,836 --> 00:24:42,137
also added a story in the trailer

581
00:24:42,157 --> 00:24:44,078
that was more appealing, like a concept,

582
00:24:45,018 --> 00:24:46,999
and sent it out again to press.

583
00:24:47,459 --> 00:24:50,361
And what happened in the end was the second trailer

584
00:24:50,381 --> 00:24:52,662
got 40,000 extra views on top to the first one,

585
00:24:53,182 --> 00:24:54,743
and it got over 60 articles more.

586
00:24:54,763 --> 00:24:55,923
And a lot of press were thinking,

587
00:24:56,063 --> 00:24:57,784
we just announced the game with the second trailer.

588
00:25:00,937 --> 00:25:04,741
And number five is, I would definitely recommend you

589
00:25:05,281 --> 00:25:07,143
to do pull PR instead of push PR.

590
00:25:07,383 --> 00:25:08,904
What I mean by that, I know it's tempting,

591
00:25:08,924 --> 00:25:10,546
you have something you want to share with the world,

592
00:25:11,026 --> 00:25:12,287
and just go out there and rub it

593
00:25:12,327 --> 00:25:13,929
in all the journalist's face all the time

594
00:25:13,949 --> 00:25:15,110
and you want to get covered everywhere.

595
00:25:15,970 --> 00:25:17,852
Which can work sometimes, but usually it doesn't.

596
00:25:18,292 --> 00:25:19,273
It makes much more sense.

597
00:25:19,807 --> 00:25:23,608
to properly find out which websites usually cover that kind of games you're talking about

598
00:25:24,069 --> 00:25:29,671
and also find out what editor likes. So really going in depth, listening to their podcasts,

599
00:25:29,791 --> 00:25:33,133
reading their articles, getting familiar with the sites that are important for you

600
00:25:33,873 --> 00:25:39,516
and then just serving them something interesting. You're already like kind of writing up the story

601
00:25:39,956 --> 00:25:44,558
for them. You sent them a very detailed pitch of what they could write about.

602
00:25:45,153 --> 00:25:46,894
But that is really, even as a small game,

603
00:25:46,954 --> 00:25:49,437
how you can get on board with a Kotaku or a Polygon.

604
00:25:49,857 --> 00:25:51,738
Because you really know that that is an angle

605
00:25:51,758 --> 00:25:52,679
that that editor likes.

606
00:25:52,779 --> 00:25:55,281
And I think if it gives them that assets and that story,

607
00:25:55,321 --> 00:25:55,782
it could work.

608
00:25:56,583 --> 00:25:59,205
So I think sending out a big press release campaign

609
00:25:59,245 --> 00:26:00,966
to a few hundred people definitely doesn't hurt.

610
00:26:01,287 --> 00:26:03,308
And it's always a good second plan.

611
00:26:03,829 --> 00:26:05,850
But to really get the spicy, really good coverage,

612
00:26:05,970 --> 00:26:08,152
it is really good to have some poor PR

613
00:26:08,172 --> 00:26:10,294
and have something interesting that the editor actually wants

614
00:26:10,394 --> 00:26:11,635
instead of forcing him to write it.

615
00:26:13,736 --> 00:26:16,837
And now we're going to talk quickly about 5 future trends in indie games PR.

616
00:26:18,497 --> 00:26:22,158
One is, I think it will be even in the future, even more than now, it will be

617
00:26:23,098 --> 00:26:25,239
more focused on high compact quality info.

618
00:26:25,659 --> 00:26:28,440
That's just with more games coming out but not more press coming up.

619
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:32,061
You will have to use more of those new speeds we talked about and bundle them up

620
00:26:32,261 --> 00:26:33,201
even more in the future

621
00:26:33,701 --> 00:26:36,602
and waste more of your PR ammunition to even cut through to press.

622
00:26:38,579 --> 00:26:42,903
I think visual content will be more important, again, because of YouTube, Snapchat, all that,

623
00:26:43,023 --> 00:26:47,167
attention spans just go down. So I think having nice GIFs is kind of essential now.

624
00:26:47,748 --> 00:26:50,811
Having a really nice short trailer gets more and more and more important.

625
00:26:52,753 --> 00:26:58,058
PR marketing will get even closer. That has to do with a few different things. One of is that

626
00:26:58,078 --> 00:27:01,821
streamers and YouTubers, they just get more commercialized and they often won't have a

627
00:27:01,861 --> 00:27:03,743
revenue share or some money to cover your game.

628
00:27:04,373 --> 00:27:10,336
And also, there are a lot of editorial houses and publishing houses having a tougher time now and start buying each other.

629
00:27:10,436 --> 00:27:14,557
And marketing deals just get more important to get all your stories off the ground.

630
00:27:17,538 --> 00:27:19,859
I think credibility through platform will vanish.

631
00:27:20,759 --> 00:27:22,960
A few years back, it was a big deal if you were on Steam.

632
00:27:23,180 --> 00:27:26,661
If you were on Steam, you've pretty much made it and everybody knew you were a proper good game.

633
00:27:28,773 --> 00:27:29,313
That is gone.

634
00:27:29,553 --> 00:27:30,593
If you're on Steam, that's cool.

635
00:27:30,933 --> 00:27:31,934
But there's so many games on Steam

636
00:27:31,954 --> 00:27:32,994
that just doesn't work anymore.

637
00:27:33,214 --> 00:27:35,655
If you come on console now, it still gives you some

638
00:27:35,695 --> 00:27:37,655
credibility, but it always gets less.

639
00:27:37,735 --> 00:27:41,436
Also, with programs like with ID at Xbox, just more games

640
00:27:41,496 --> 00:27:41,996
are coming out.

641
00:27:42,476 --> 00:27:45,637
So just pretending or saying you're on a platform now

642
00:27:45,717 --> 00:27:47,878
doesn't give you as much boost as it did back in the day.

643
00:27:50,438 --> 00:27:53,919
And one last thing that I think will take off even more.

644
00:27:54,684 --> 00:27:56,225
It's clever in-game social sharing.

645
00:27:56,405 --> 00:27:58,527
What I mean by that, one example is again, super hot.

646
00:27:58,907 --> 00:28:00,588
If I were to share what it is, it would be a spoiler.

647
00:28:01,249 --> 00:28:04,050
But we have one example from a game called Alpha Bear,

648
00:28:04,271 --> 00:28:06,452
which is a puzzle game where you're puzzled with words.

649
00:28:07,173 --> 00:28:09,074
By the end of each level, they have certain templates

650
00:28:09,094 --> 00:28:11,976
with sentences, and depending on which words you created,

651
00:28:12,576 --> 00:28:14,397
different words are filled in into the template.

652
00:28:14,858 --> 00:28:17,459
And a lot of times, the thing that comes out in the end

653
00:28:17,499 --> 00:28:18,340
doesn't make any sense.

654
00:28:18,960 --> 00:28:20,621
Sometimes, things like that come out.

655
00:28:21,712 --> 00:28:22,952
And people really like that.

656
00:28:22,992 --> 00:28:24,133
And people think that's funny.

657
00:28:24,273 --> 00:28:25,614
And they share it on the social media.

658
00:28:25,974 --> 00:28:27,975
And they don't do it because they get an in-game bonus.

659
00:28:28,656 --> 00:28:30,337
They don't do it because they get an extra thing.

660
00:28:30,477 --> 00:28:31,617
They get it because they want to.

661
00:28:32,278 --> 00:28:33,018
And this was brilliant.

662
00:28:33,058 --> 00:28:36,140
I tell you, when AlphaBear came out, I didn't pay attention.

663
00:28:36,200 --> 00:28:37,981
But my timeline was flooded for days.

664
00:28:38,041 --> 00:28:38,802
And it came back.

665
00:28:38,862 --> 00:28:40,402
And again, and finally, I was like, OK,

666
00:28:40,422 --> 00:28:41,363
I want to check out AlphaBear.

667
00:28:41,383 --> 00:28:42,504
And I downloaded it and played it.

668
00:28:43,124 --> 00:28:45,866
So I think that's really a way to go forward.

669
00:28:48,219 --> 00:28:53,825
and to also fight against the things like that it's getting more difficult to get streamers and press to listen to you.

670
00:28:55,386 --> 00:28:57,248
That's it from my side. Thanks a lot for listening.

671
00:29:06,978 --> 00:29:12,003
I think we're pretty much on time or out of time, but if anyone has questions, I will be around here and also in the wrap-up room later.

